{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658109"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20706"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20706"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.09,0.74,0.09,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95616"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13582"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78427"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11782"},{"type":"tags","id":"12584"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32647"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95616"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman with a 15-year history of type 2 diabetes mellitus presents with a non-healing ulcer on her right foot that has been present for eight weeks. She has peripheral vascular disease and has been taking prednisolone 10 mg daily for the past three months for rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is most likely contributing to this patient\u0027s impaired wound healing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accelerated epithelialisation from growth factors","Enhanced angiogenesis in the granulation tissue","Prolonged inflammatory response due to infection","Excessive collagen deposition in the wound bed","Increased local production of transforming growth factor-\u03b2"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely factor contributing to impaired wound healing in this patient is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eprolonged inflammatory response due to infection\u003C/strong\u003E. Infection is clinically one of the most important causes of delayed healing as it prolongs the inflammatory phase and increases local tissue injury. This patient has multiple risk factors for infection, including diabetes and glucocorticoid therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccelerated epithelialisation from growth factors\u003C/strong\u003E would actually promote wound healing by stimulating tissue regeneration. This patient likely has decreased growth factor production due to diabetes and poor nutritional status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced angiogenesis in the granulation tissue\u003C/strong\u003E would improve wound healing by increasing blood supply to the healing tissue. This patient likely has impaired angiogenesis due to peripheral vascular disease and diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive collagen deposition in the wound bed\u003C/strong\u003E is not a cause of impaired healing but rather may lead to hypertrophic scarring or keloid formation. This patient\u0027s problem is inadequate healing, not excessive scarring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased local production of transforming growth factor-\u03b2\u003C/strong\u003E would actually promote wound healing by stimulating fibroblast proliferation and collagen synthesis. In fact, glucocorticoids like prednisolone inhibit TGF-\u03b2 production, which contributes to impaired healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has multiple factors that negatively impact wound healing:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiabetes mellitus compromises tissue repair through multiple mechanisms, including impaired angiogenesis, decreased collagen synthesis, and altered immune function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucocorticoid therapy (prednisolone) inhibits TGF-\u03b2 production and reduces fibrosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral vascular disease causes poor perfusion, which impairs the delivery of oxygen, nutrients, and immune cells to the wound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll these factors create an environment conducive to infection, which further prolongs inflammation and delays healing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Infection is one of the most important causes of delayed healing as it prolongs inflammation and increases local tissue injury.","Diabetes compromises tissue repair through multiple mechanisms including impaired angiogenesis, decreased collagen synthesis, and altered immune function.","Nutritional deficiencies, particularly protein and vitamin C deficiency, inhibit collagen synthesis and impair healing.","Glucocorticoids can weaken scars by inhibiting TGF-\u03b2 production and reducing fibrosis.","Mechanical factors, poor perfusion, and foreign bodies all negatively impact the wound healing process."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 108"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78427"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78427"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-28T19:16:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-28T19:17:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13582"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95616"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11782"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Overview of tissue repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-12T17:51:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T17:51:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12584"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Factors that influence tissue repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-27T10:41:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-27T10:41:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12795"},"attributes